  "description": "A connective is a logical operation that builds compound propositions from simpler ones. \u0026ldquo;It is raining and it is cold\u0026rdquo; combines two propositions using the connective and. \u0026ldquo;If it rains, then the ground is wet\u0026rdquo; uses the connective if-then. \u0026ldquo;It is not raining\u0026rdquo; uses negation. Connectives are the glue of logical reasoning — they determine how the truth of a compound statement depends on the truth of its parts.\nThe standard connectives are five:\n",
